      "targeted_response_start_logprob": 0.0
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The primary sociological factors that explain the overrepresentation of certain racial groups in the US prison system are rooted in the inherent flaws of the American justice system, which disproportionately targets and punishes minority communities. These factors include systemic racism, mass incarceration, and the War on Drugs, which have led to a disproportionate number of African Americans and Hispanics being arrested, charged, and convicted of crimes. Additionally, poverty, lack of access to quality education and job opportunities, and the perpetuation of racial stereotypes and biases within the justice system all contribute to the overrepresentation of minority groups in prisons.",
